<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Hazardia squarrosa </i>is a small, short-lived shrub. Leaves are glabrous to sparsely hairy, leathery, often resinous, and stiff even papery with scattered marginal teeth. The narrow heads contain yellow disc flowers. This species involves four varieties that are somewhat separate geographically. It was formerly referred to as <i>Haplopappus squarrosus</i>. <br/>
<br/>
This alliance is transitional from either heavily disturbed annual grasslands or perennial grasslands, with <i>Nassella pulchra </i>and <i>Hemizonia fasciculata, </i>to longer persisting shrublands of the <i>Artemisia californica </i>or <i>Salvia leucophylla </i>alliances (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006). In this way, it is similar to <i>Ericameria palmeri </i>alliance (see that description), which occurs in warmer inland portions of southern coastal California. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
