    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Hazardia squarrosa</i> includes Central California Coast (261A), Central California Coast Ranges (M262A), Great Valley (262A), Sierra Nevada Foothills (M261F), and Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb, Bd-g). Stands at Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) vary in structure and species composition. Stands are likely in other subsections.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Hazardia squarrosa </i>is a common, early seral species that does well following mechanical disturbance or fire. Stands tend to have higher native herbaceous component than many other adjacent shrublands. While some stands may transition over time to denser stands of the <i>Artemisia californica </i>or <i>Salvia leucophylla </i>alliances, other stands on heavy clay appear to be stable (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006). </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Associations</h4>
        
            
            <ul class="text">
                
                    <li>Hazardia squarrosa - Artemisia californica [1]</li>
                
                    <li>Hazardia squarrosa / Nassella pulchra - Deinandra fasciculata [1], [2]</li>
                
            </ul>
        
    </div>

    
